# Setup of the shiny server for pcaExplorer, ideal and co


## Ubuntu setup

```{bash}
mkdir marinif
cd marinif
wget https://mirrors.cicku.me/CRAN/src/base/R-3/R-3.3.2.tar.gz

tar xvfz R-3.3.2.tar.gz


ll

cd R-3.3.2
ll
./configure --prefix /usr/local/bin/R-3.3.2

# configure: error: No F77 compiler found

# http://stackoverflow.com/questions/17720430/error-running-r-in-linux
apt-get install gfortran
./configure --prefix /usr/local/bin/R-3.3.2

# configure: error: --with-readline=yes (default) and headers/libs are not available


http://stackoverflow.com/questions/17473547/error-with-readline-yes-default-and-headers-libs-are-not-available

apt-get install build-essential
apt-get install fort77
apt-get install liblzma-dev  libblas-dev gfortran
apt-get install gcc-multilib
apt-get install gobjc++
# sudo apt-get install aptitude
apt-get install libreadline-dev



apt-get install xorg-dev
sudo apt-get upgrade -f

# will install without x11...

./configure --prefix /usr/local/bin/R-3.3.2 --with-x=no

# checking whether bzip2 support suffices... configure: error: bzip2 library and headers are required

apt-get install libbz2-dev

./configure --prefix /usr/local/bin/R-3.3.2 --with-x=no

# checking whether PCRE support suffices... configure: error: pcre >= 8.10 library and headers are required
sudo apt-get install libpcre3-dev

# configure: error: libcurl >= 7.28.0 library and headers are required with support for https

apt-get install libcurl4-openssl-dev 

./configure --prefix /usr/local/bin/R-3.3.2 --with-x=no

apt-get install libjpeg-dev 
apt-get install libtiff5-dev 
apt-get install texinfo


# good docs:

https://zerk.canopus.uberspace.de/Guides/shiny-server/

apt-get install texlive-basic
apt-get install texlive-fonts-recommended
apt-get install fonts-inconsolata
```

and then install the binary package---


```{r}
https://www.r-bloggers.com/how-to-install-r-on-linux-ubuntu-16-04-xenial-xerus/
1. Add R repository

First, we’ve got to add a line to our /etc/apt/sources.list file. This can be accomplished with the following. Note the “xenial” in the line, indicating Ubuntu 16.04. If you have a different version, just change that.

sudo echo "deb http://cran.rstudio.com/bin/linux/ubuntu xenial/" | sudo tee -a /etc/apt/sources.list

2. Add R to Ubuntu Keyring

First:

 gpg --keyserver keyserver.ubuntu.com --recv-key E084DAB9

Then:

 gpg -a --export E084DAB9 | sudo apt-key add -

3. Install R-Base

Most Linux users should be familiar with the old…

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install r-base r-base-dev
  
```
